'''Physical biochemistry''' is a branch of [[biochemistry]] that deals with the theory, techniques and methodology used to study the [[physical chemistry]] of [[biomolecule]]s.<ref name="Freifelder1982">{{cite book|author=David Freifelder|title=Physical Biochemistry: Applications to Biochemistry and Molecular Biology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YLKXYRl4EzUC|date=15 August 1982|publisher=W. H. Freeman|isbn=978-0-7167-1444-6}}</ref> It also deals with the mathematical approaches for the analysis of [[Biochemistry|biochemical reaction]] and the [[Modelling biological systems|modelling of biological systems]]. It provides insight to the structure of macromolecules, and how chemical structure influences physical properties of a biological substance.<ref name="Sheehan2013">{{cite book|author=David Sheehan|title=Physical Biochemistry: Principles and Applications|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AxxbYlsuZrwC&pg=PP10|date=30 April 2013|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-118-68748-2|pages=10–}}</ref>
